passages.text: Shares of OLLI traded up \((+0.6\%)\) at market close vs. \(+0.3\%\) for the S&P 500) due to the earnings beat and FY25 guidance raise. Key takeaways from the quarter include: 1) Increased focus on engagement with OLLI Army members should drive sales, as seen by their successful June Army Night; 2) Strong deal flow and product pipeline drives margin beats despite higher SG&A costs; and 3) Stores continue to outperform, with potential for more unit growth in 2026.

We reiterate our Buy rating on OLLI as the company continues to thrive on supply chain disruption, closeout product from retail bankruptcies, and attractive vendor partnerships. Bankruptcies have also increased the optionality for real estate and we see potential upside to stores opening in 2025 and 2026. While OLLI raised their FY25 guidance, we note that management tends to be conservative as 4Q guidance remains unchanged with a LSD comp; we highlight that OLLI will likely see further strength into the 2H as their product pipeline continues to maintain strong price gaps. Moreover, we are constructive on their focused priority towards acquiring new OLLI Army members, as it will drive stronger top- line performance and increase their market share. The success of their recent June Army Night is indicative of the member engagement they can have during the Holiday season. We raise our price target to \(\) 158\(from\) \ \(147\)

sales: Management stated that their new June Army Night event was a success, as it surpassed all expectations and drove record customer engagement. Specifically, customer acquisition increased \(+60\%\) and many stores had long lines ( \(\sim 200\) people). Although management was expecting the impact of the event to be muted for the P&L, the Army Night drove \(+100\) bps increase in comp and sales exceeded the December Army Night. We highlight that the sales record is indicative of OLLI's compelling product pipeline and member engagement, as the event exceeded expectations despite not taking place during a Holiday period. Management is planning to apply their learnings from the July night to their December night, which could amplify sales further in the year. Given that members comprise \(80\%\) of sales and spend \(+40\%\) more per shipping trip, the increased focus on engagement events should drive

significant top- line performance from both new and repeating members. We highlight that there is also still more customer acquisition to capture, as the closed Big Lots stores have left behind many potential customers. As of 2Q25, OLLI has 16.1mn members, an increase of \(+10.6\%\) y/y.
Exhibit 1: 2025 saw the highest y/y growth rates in OLLI Army acquisition OLLI Army members and y/y member growth
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Strong deal flow and product pipeline drives margin beats despite higher SG&A costs: SG&A expenses as a percentage of sales was \(25.8\%\) this quarter (compared to GS estimate of \(25.6\%\) ), mainly driven by higher medical and casualty claims. Management stated that although they had an unusually high number of severe medical cases this quarter, they expect these expenses to eventually improve given they are seeing early signs of softening trends. Despite the higher claims, management still beat with an \(11.3\%\) operating margin (vs. GS/consensus of \(11.1\% /10.8\%\) ), driven by strong top line performance and their resulting \(39.9\%\) gross margin beat (vs. GS/consensus of \(39.5\% /39.0\%\) ). The strong gross margin was driven by merchandising margins, which benefited from strong deal flow and buying power. Specifically, because OLLI has strong vendor partnerships, they are able to negotiate deal pricing and drive better cost margins, while still obtaining compelling assortment. OLLI's size and scale, as well as their supply chain efficiencies, also contributed to this beat as they are able to take on more deal volume and flow products better through their distribution centers. Management raised their FY25 gross margin to \(40.3\%\) (vs. \(40.0\%\) prior).

Stores continue to outperform, with potential for more 2026 unit growth: The current cohort of new stores opening this year are performing above expectations, and are maintaining the mid- teen four walls and strong payback periods as historically. Most of these old Big Lots stores are also benefiting from improved planning and execution, soft opening schedules, outsized growth in Army acquisition, and the warm box dynamic. In terms of comp stores, management called out \(\sim 290\) stores that used to be surrounded by Big Lots are still seeing a \(+\) LSD to \(+\) MSD comp lift compared to the rest of the chain. For 2026, OLLI still sees significant opportunity to drive accelerated unit growth given the many bankrupt store closures. Management stated that they will likely have another year of
elevated openings, with potentially a fifth distribution center in future years.

We are adjusting our EPS estimates primarily to reflect higher comp performance in the 2H of 2025. FY25 estimates are \(3.86\) (from \(\) 3.79), and we raise our FY26 and FY27 estimate to \(\) 4.42\(from\) \ \(4.29\) and \(\) 5.07\(from\) \ \(4.93\) . We also adjust our 3Q25 estimate to \(\) 0.40\(to reflect higher earnings and also slightly higher pre - opening expenses for more store openings.
Exhibit 2: OLLI estimate change summary In \(\) 1\(millions, except per - share
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

We are Buy rated on OLLI. Our 12- month price target increases to \(\) 158\(from\) \ \(147\) prior) primarily due to higher estimates. We keep our downside/base/upside relative P/E multiples unchanged (135%/145%/155%). Our market multiple increases to 23.2x (vs. 23.0x prior)

Downside risks include a slowdown in demand, either due to macro headwinds or in response to a less attractive assortment; limited incremental benefit, if any, from trade down; trade out from their lowest- income customers; and potential margin headwinds driven by higher wages/other inflationary expenses and mix shift to lower- margin products.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
